    "keywords": "microfluidics, high-throughput screening, enzyme kinetics, transcription factor binding, protein-peptide interactions, protein stability, single-cell analysis, double emulsion droplets, MRBLEs, catch bonds, machine learning-guided design, spectrally encoded beads, droplet microfluidics, DNA binding affinity, biophysical modeling, multiplexed assays, organoid phenotyping, protein-DNA interaction, flow cytometry, microfluidic device engineering",
    "introduction": "The Fordyce Lab at Stanford University stands at the intersection of biophysics, quantitative biochemistry, and microfluidics, with a core mission to understand and engineer complex molecular interactions governing cellular function. The lab specializes in developing and applying high-throughput, quantitative methods to investigate how proteins, nucleic acids, and small molecules interact with extraordinary precision and scale. By integrating microfluidic technologies with innovative assay platforms, the Fordyce Lab pushes the frontiers of molecular biology, biotechnology, and systems biology. At the heart of the lab’s work is the pursuit of detailed biophysical models of biological processes through the measurement of kinetic and thermodynamic parameters. These parameters represent the “universal language” needed to describe and predict function in biological systems. To this end, the lab leverages a diverse suite of microfluidic platforms, including valved devices, droplet generators, and microwell arrays, enabling massively parallel biochemical measurements at single-molecule and single-cell resolution. A prominent platform developed by the lab is HT-MEK (High-Throughput Microfluidic Enzyme Kinetics), which allows rapid, multiplexed quantification of enzyme activity across large mutant libraries. This tool has enabled mapping of sequence-to-function landscapes and facilitated the development of predictive models for enzyme behavior—critical for rational enzyme design and precision medicine. Similarly, MITOMI (Mechanically Induced Trapping of Molecular Interactions) and BET-seq platforms are used to dissect transcription factor (TF) binding specificities by measuring binding energies across millions of DNA sequences in parallel. These approaches reveal how mutations, flanking sequences, and structural motifs impact TF-DNA interactions. Another flagship innovation is the MRBLE (Microspheres with Ratiometric Barcode Lanthanide Encoding) platform, which creates uniquely barcoded hydrogel beads for multiplexed molecular assays. MRBLE-pep extends this technology to protein-peptide interactions, while MRBLE-path allows simultaneous detection of multiple pathogens—demonstrating utility across structural biology, immunology, and infectious disease diagnostics. The lab also pioneers droplet microfluidics through the Dropception platform, enabling generation and sorting of double emulsion droplets. This technology supports single-cell encapsulation, multi-omics assays, and kinetic tracking of biological processes at scale. Applications span from immune profiling to screening of slow-growing microbes and plant biosynthetic cells. The Fordyce Lab maintains a commitment to open science, making protocols, design files, and datasets available via OSF repositories. Their collaborative and educational ethos is reflected in the Microfluidics Foundry course, where students design real-world devices to tackle unmet biological needs. Through a synergistic blend of engineering, computation, and molecular biology, the Fordyce Lab is redefining how we study biological interactions, bridging the gap between fundamental discovery and applied biomedical science. Their contributions are not only methodological but conceptual, offering transformative insights into the molecular logic of life."
